post_cb({"28498941": {"ParentId": "28498880", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>Yes, author of that is incorrect on how the default constructors work. He may have confuse it with copy constructor which is created automatically even in his case.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "4538344", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "28498941", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2015-02-13T11:49:04.773", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-13T11:49:04.773"}, "28498880": {"CommentCount": "5", "ViewCount": "274", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "4541072", "CreationDate": "2015-02-13T11:45:56.963", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-14T08:59:44.237", "Title": "\u0421++ Private Default Constructor with Empty Body", "AcceptedAnswerId": "28498931", "LastEditDate": "2015-02-14T08:59:44.237", "Id": "28498880", "Score": "1", "Body": "<p>I saw some code <a href=\"http://www.learncpp.com/cpp-tutorial/102-composition/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>There is a class with a private default constructor with empty body and a parameterized constructor.\nCode comments say that the default constructor was made private \"so that it would <em>not</em> be possible to create objects with no properties specified\" [properties are represented by class data members]. Thus there is no use in explicitly defining a private default constructor because it cannot be utilized!</p>\n<p>Once we declared a parameterized constructor a default constructor will not be implicitly supplied by the compiler! Thus there will be no way to create objects with no arguments passed to nonexistent constructor.</p>\n<p>My question is why do we need to declare a default constructor in this case <em>at all</em>?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><default-constructor>", "OwnerUserId": "4541072", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_28498880_28498931_0": {"section_id": 369, "quality": 0.9444444444444444, "length": 17}}, "n3337": {"so_28498880_28498931_0": {"section_id": 359, "quality": 0.9444444444444444, "length": 17}}, "n4659": {"so_28498880_28498931_0": {"section_id": 381, "quality": 0.8333333333333334, "length": 15}}}, "28498931": {"ParentId": "28498880", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>You are completely correct.\nAs soon as there is a custom constructor no default constructor will be created.</p>\n<p>So you don't need to declare a default constructor in this case.</p>\n<p>Also see <strong>\u00a7 12.1 / 5</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_28498880_28498931_0\">A <em>default</em> constructor for a class <code>X</code> is a constructor of class <code>X</code> that can be called without an argument. If there is no user-declared constructor for class <code>X</code>, a constructor having no parameters is implicitly declared\n  as defaulted (8.4). [...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3893186", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "28498931", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2015-02-13T11:48:40.657", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-13T11:48:40.657"}});